MALE NARRATOR:<i> Hi.
 Hey, you good? Not for long.</i>

00:00:21.420 --> 00:00:22.855
<i> Welcome
 to another</i> Nightly Show

00:00:22.888 --> 00:00:25.859
<i> Super Depressing Deep Dive.</i>

00:00:27.059 --> 00:00:28.594
<i> Everyone's talking about them.</i>

00:00:28.627 --> 00:00:31.431
One of the greatest public
health crises of our time,

00:00:31.464 --> 00:00:33.099
the opioid epidemic.

00:00:33.132 --> 00:00:34.834
MAN:
<i> An epidemic of drug abuse.</i>

00:00:34.867 --> 00:00:37.103
We are seeing more people killed

00:00:37.136 --> 00:00:41.607
because of opioid overdose
than traffic accidents.

00:00:41.640 --> 00:00:43.109
(tires squealing, static)

00:00:44.210 --> 00:00:45.344
NARRATOR:
<i> So how did this happen?</i>

00:00:45.377 --> 00:00:46.913
<i> It starts with pain.</i>

00:00:46.946 --> 00:00:49.615
-(groaning)<i> -People hate pain, 
 mainly because it's painful,</i>

00:00:49.648 --> 00:00:51.784
<i> and opioids take that pain
 and turn it into...</i>

00:00:51.817 --> 00:00:55.388
♪ Magic body warmth! ♪

00:00:55.421 --> 00:00:58.291
<i> Opioids are any opium-like
 compound, like morphine,</i>

00:00:58.324 --> 00:01:01.027
<i> invented in 1827
 and advertised to children.</i>

00:01:01.060 --> 00:01:02.495
<i> Yes, that baby won't cry.</i>

00:01:02.528 --> 00:01:04.664
<i> Well, until you take away
 its sweet, sweet morphine.</i>

00:01:04.697 --> 00:01:05.932
(crying)

00:01:05.965 --> 00:01:07.366
<i> In 1898, Bayer tried</i>

00:01:07.399 --> 00:01:09.035
<i> to make a less-addictive
 morphine called... heroin.</i>

00:01:09.068 --> 00:01:10.336
♪ Heroin! ♪

00:01:10.369 --> 00:01:11.871
<i> Now, selling legal heroin
 may sound crazy,</i>

00:01:11.904 --> 00:01:13.539
<i> but this is during the time</i>

00:01:13.572 --> 00:01:15.141
<i> when you could get cocaine in
 Coca-Cola, and doctors thought</i>

00:01:15.174 --> 00:01:17.143
<i> your skull shape determined
 how smart you were.</i>

00:01:17.176 --> 00:01:18.511
Phrenology.

00:01:18.544 --> 00:01:21.013
<i> In the 1970s and '80s,
 most doctors avoided opioids</i>

00:01:21.046 --> 00:01:22.315
<i> as long-term pain relief</i>

00:01:22.348 --> 00:01:24.283
<i> because
 of the whole addiction thing.</i>

00:01:24.316 --> 00:01:26.352
<i> But in 1995,
 Purdue Pharmaceuticals--</i>

00:01:26.385 --> 00:01:28.154
<i> sadly not a branch
 of Perdue Chicken--</i>

00:01:28.187 --> 00:01:29.689
<i> marketed the safest opioid
 of all.</i>

00:01:29.722 --> 00:01:32.692
♪ Oxycontin! Oxycontin! ♪

00:01:32.725 --> 00:01:36.162
<i> And everyone was happy
and pain-free forever. The end.</i>

00:01:36.195 --> 00:01:38.231
<i> JK. Pain is life.
 It will never go away.</i>

00:01:38.264 --> 00:01:40.233
<i> -Like U2 and Guy Fieri.</i>
 -(boy shouts)

00:01:40.266 --> 00:01:42.235
<i>And hey, it turns out Oxycontin
 is crazy addictive,</i>

00:01:42.268 --> 00:01:44.237
<i> but to make it seem
mega-awesome, Purdue handed out</i>

00:01:44.270 --> 00:01:47.039
<i> branded promotional items,
 like fishing hats and CDs.</i>

00:01:47.072 --> 00:01:49.308
<i> Yes, that's the title.
 It isn't even clever,</i>

00:01:49.341 --> 00:01:50.576
<i> like Oxycontin-Eyed Joe!</i>

00:01:50.609 --> 00:01:51.811
<i> There were also plush toys,</i>

00:01:51.844 --> 00:01:53.212
<i> which we couldn't
 find images of,</i>

00:01:53.245 --> 00:01:54.881
<i> so we assume
 they look like this.</i>

00:01:54.914 --> 00:01:57.383
TOY BEAR:
Hug me. I can't feel pain.

00:01:57.416 --> 00:01:59.519
(winding down):
I'm a bear...

00:01:59.552 --> 00:02:01.554
<i> And to help ease
 everyone's fear of addiction,</i>

00:02:01.587 --> 00:02:03.756
<i> Purdue created videos
 with super trustworthy dudes.</i>

00:02:03.789 --> 00:02:05.925 line:0%
They don't wear out.
They go on working.

00:02:05.958 --> 00:02:08.461 line:0%
They do not have
serious medical side effects.

00:02:08.494 --> 00:02:09.929
<i> Thank you kindly,
 doctor-type guy</i>

00:02:09.962 --> 00:02:11.564
<i> who was totally not paid
 to say that.</i>

00:02:11.597 --> 00:02:13.166
<i> I bet he was paid to say that.</i>

00:02:13.199 --> 00:02:14.433
<i> A year later,
 opioid prescriptions</i>

00:02:14.466 --> 00:02:15.834
<i> jumped by $11 million. </i>

00:02:15.868 --> 00:02:17.837
<i> Those are some Viagra-level
 numbers, but without the ads</i>

00:02:17.870 --> 00:02:19.872
<i> that make you think
 of your parents doing it.</i>

00:02:19.905 --> 00:02:22.475
<i> Sales of Oxycontin went
 from $44 million in 1996...</i>

00:02:22.508 --> 00:02:24.944
MAN:
Triple-decker yacht money!

00:02:24.977 --> 00:02:28.247
<i> ...to $1.5 billion in 2002.</i>

00:02:28.280 --> 00:02:30.316
MEN:
Ya-Ya-Yacht jet!

00:02:30.349 --> 00:02:33.219
<i> By 2012, doctors wrote more
 than 259 million prescriptions</i>

00:02:33.252 --> 00:02:35.021
<i> for opioids--
 enough to give a bottle</i>

00:02:35.054 --> 00:02:36.355
<i> to every adult in America.</i>

00:02:36.388 --> 00:02:38.090
<i> You don't have to be
 a chicken scientist</i>

00:02:38.123 --> 00:02:39.592
<i> to know that when
 everyone's got opioids,</i>

00:02:39.625 --> 00:02:41.594
<i> opioid overdoses
 are going to skyrocket.</i>

00:02:41.627 --> 00:02:43.930
<i> More than 165,000 people
 have died of causes</i>

00:02:43.963 --> 00:02:45.932
<i> related to painkiller use
 since 1999,</i>

00:02:45.965 --> 00:02:48.901
<i> including the men who love
 to party like it's 1999.</i>

00:02:48.934 --> 00:02:51.170
NEWSWOMAN:<i> Tests show
 the music icon Prince</i>

00:02:51.203 --> 00:02:53.172
<i> died of an opioid overdose.</i>

00:02:53.205 --> 00:02:55.441
NARRATOR:<i> That's right, those
 greedy drug company bastards</i>

00:02:55.474 --> 00:02:57.210
<i> mother(bleep) killed...</i>

